| \"Material\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lie Like Me\"\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Restless Minds''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n! scope=\"row\" | \"No Filter\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"One More Goodbye\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"20\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a single that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! style=\"width:12em;\"| Video\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2014\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Footnotes (Happy Endings)\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Good And The Right\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Push For The Stride\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Way Back When\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2016\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Carry You Home\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Guilty Flowers\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cartwheels\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Boomerang\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Material\"\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lie Like Me\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wardthomasmusic.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Country music duos]]\n[[Category:English country music groups]]\n[[Category:British country singers]]\n[[Category:Twin musical duos]]\n[[Category:Female musical duos]]\n\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "NOLA1982", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix typo in wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ward_Thomas_(band)"}
{"title_page": "E.M.I.L.Y.", "text_new": "'''E.M.I.L.Y.''' (sometimes, '''EMILY''' or '''[[Emily]]'''; acronym for '''Emergency Integrated Lifesaving Lanyard''') is a robotic device used by [[lifeguard]]s for rescuing swimmers. It operates on battery power and is operated by [[remote control]]<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news|publisher=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2012/05/robot-lifeguard-emily-patrols-the-beach/|author=Alyssa Newcomb|title=Robot Lifeguard [[EmilyTK]] Patrols the Beach|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref> after being dropped into the water from shore, a boat or pier, or helicopter.<ref name=\"nn\"/> Using an [[impeller]] motor to travel through water, it is able to reach victims much faster than a human lifeguard can by swimming, and it is more compact and less expensive to maintain than manned watercraft. It can also operate in weather and surf conditions that make other rescue attempts impractical.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|publisher=WBUR News|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/technology/robotic-lifeguard-emily-assist-lifeguards-10843.html|date=July 18, 2012|author=|title=Robotic lifeguard [[EmilyTK]] to assist lifeguards at beaches across the country}}</ref> Once it reaches the victims its foam core allows it to function as a [[flotation device]] for up to 4-6 people holding onto side ropes or handles.<ref name=\"cnn\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\nFire and rescue crews put robot rescuer EMILY to the test|url=http://www.kmtr.com/news/local/story/Fire-and-rescue-crews-put-robot-rescuer-EMILY-to/ce6jz8rWQkmr5vT8C8CBeQ.cspx|publisher=KMTR News|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref> \n\nEmily was created by inventor Anthony Mulligan and Robert Lautrup, and named after Marie Mulligan's friend, who died in a car accident.<ref name=\"abc\"/> It was first tested in [[Zuma Beach]] near [[Malibu, California]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/10/25/technology/robot_lifeguard/index.htm|date=October 25, 2012|author=Cindy Waxer|title=A robot lifeguard patrols Malibu}}</ref> and at [[Depoe Bay, Oregon]] and [[Westerly, Rhode Island]] beginning early 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robot lifeguards hit the beach in time for summer|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/futureoftech/robot-lifeguards-hit-beach-time-summer-801275|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|author=John Roach}}</ref> In July 2012, lifeguards there made one of the first rescues using [[EmilyTK]], pulling both her partner and her son to shore after they had been caught in a [[rip current]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=The News Guard|url=http://www.thenewsguard.com/news/article_615199a4-d10a-11e1-86ba-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Depoe Bay Fire rescues two from rip current with first use of EMILY|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA new multi-day duration gasoline powered variant of EMILY for ocean-based storm tracking and weather data collection has been developed under funding by NOAA.\n\nIn January 2016 [[EmilyTK]] joined a Roboticists Without Borders team from The University of Texas A&M Center for Robotic Assisted Search and Rescue on a successful mission to Lesvos Island, Greece to assist in ocean rescues of Syrian refugees crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece.  In the first few days of embedded missions with the Hellenic Red Cross, EMILY assisted the Red Cross and other lifeguard organizations to help 250+ refugees safely come ashore on Lesvos.  There are currently systems with the Hellenic Red Cross, the Hellenic Coast Guard, and in Turkey.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2016/03/22/471285293/how-a-high-tech-buoy-named-emily-could-save-migrants-off-greece\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140828021816/http://www.hydronalix.com/home.html hydronalix.com] - official site for manufacturer\n*[http://www.emilyrobot.com emilyrobot.com]\n\n[[Category:Robotics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sea rescue]]\n\nhttps://www.wired.com/2016/01/a-robot-life-preserver-goes-to-work-in-the-greek-refugee-crisis/\n", "text_old": "'''E.M.I.L.Y.''' (sometimes, '''EMILY''' or '''Emily'''; acronym for '''Emergency Integrated Lifesaving Lanyard''') is a robotic device used by [[lifeguard]]s for rescuing swimmers. It operates on battery power and is operated by [[remote control]]<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news|publisher=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2012/05/robot-lifeguard-emily-patrols-the-beach/|author=Alyssa Newcomb|title=Robot Lifeguard \u2018Emily\u2019 Patrols the Beach|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref> after being dropped into the water from shore, a boat or pier, or helicopter.<ref name=\"nn\"/> Using an [[impeller]] motor to travel through water, it is able to reach victims much faster than a human lifeguard can by swimming, and it is more compact and less expensive to maintain than manned watercraft. It can also operate in weather and surf conditions that make other rescue attempts impractical.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|publisher=WBUR News|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/technology/robotic-lifeguard-emily-assist-lifeguards-10843.html|date=July 18, 2012|author=|title=Robotic lifeguard 'Emily' to assist lifeguards at beaches across the country}}</ref> Once it reaches the victims its foam core allows it to function as a [[flotation device]] for up to 4-6 people holding onto side ropes or handles.<ref name=\"cnn\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\nFire and rescue crews put robot rescuer EMILY to the test|url=http://www.kmtr.com/news/local/story/Fire-and-rescue-crews-put-robot-rescuer-EMILY-to/ce6jz8rWQkmr5vT8C8CBeQ.cspx|publisher=KMTR News|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref> \n\nEmily was created by inventor Anthony Mulligan and Robert Lautrup, and named after Marie Mulligan's friend, who died in a car accident.<ref name=\"abc\"/> It was first tested in [[Zuma Beach]] near [[Malibu, California]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/10/25/technology/robot_lifeguard/index.htm|date=October 25, 2012|author=Cindy Waxer|title=A robot lifeguard patrols Malibu}}</ref> and at [[Depoe Bay, Oregon]] and [[Westerly, Rhode Island]] beginning early 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robot lifeguards hit the beach in time for summer|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/futureoftech/robot-lifeguards-hit-beach-time-summer-801275|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|author=John Roach}}</ref> In July 2012, lifeguards there made one of the first rescues using Emily, pulling a father and son to shore after they had been caught in a [[rip current]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=The News Guard|url=http://www.thenewsguard.com/news/article_615199a4-d10a-11e1-86ba-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Depoe Bay Fire rescues two from rip current with first use of EMILY|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA new multi-day duration gasoline powered variant of EMILY for ocean-based storm tracking and weather data collection has been developed under funding by NOAA.\n\nIn January 2016 EMILY joined a Roboticists Without Borders team from The University of Texas A&M Center for Robotic Assisted Search and Rescue on a successful mission to Lesvos Island, Greece to assist in ocean rescues of Syrian refugees crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece.  In the first few days of embedded missions with the Hellenic Red Cross, EMILY assisted the Red Cross and other lifeguard organizations to help 250+ refugees safely come ashore on Lesvos.  There are currently systems with the Hellenic Red Cross, the Hellenic Coast Guard, and in Turkey.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2016/03/22/471285293/how-a-high-tech-buoy-named-emily-could-save-migrants-off-greece\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140828021816/http://www.hydronalix.com/home.html hydronalix.com] - official site for manufacturer\n*[http://www.emilyrobot.com emilyrobot.com]\n\n[[Category:Robotics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sea rescue]]\n\nhttps://www.wired.com/2016/01/a-robot-life-preserver-goes-to-work-in-the-greek-refugee-crisis/\n", "name_user": "Annikablohm", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E.M.I.L.Y."}
{"title_page": "C. Gregg Singer", "text_new": "'''Charles Gregg Singer''' (1910 \u2013 22 March 1999) was an American historian and theologian. He was born in Philadelphia, and studied at [[Haverford College]], and the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. Singer taught at [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]], [[Salem College]], the [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[Belhaven College]], [[Catawba College]], [[Furman University]], and [[Greenville Presbyterian Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Papers\">{{cite web |title=C. Gregg Singer Papers |url=http://www.pcahistory.org/findingaids/singer.html |publisher=[[Presbyterian Church in America]] Historical Center |accessdate=12 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812053648/http://www.pcahistory.org/findingaids/singer.html |archive-date=12 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSinger was involved in the formation of the [[Presbyterian Church in America]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Posner |first1=Sarah |title=Neo-Confederates and the Revival of \"Theological War\" for the \"Christian Nation\" |url=http://religiondispatches.org/neo-confederates-and-the-revival-of-theological-war-for-the-christian-nation/ |accessdate=12 August 2018 |work=[[Religion Dispatches]] |date=13 July 2011}}</ref> as the last President of Concerned Presbyterians, a laymans' group within the [[Presbyterian Church in the United States]].<ref name=\"Papers\" /> Singer left the PCUS in 1975, and joined the [[Associate Reformed Presbyterian Church]], before finally joining the PCA in 1987.<ref name=\"Papers\" />\n\nSinger is best known for his 1964 work, ''A Theological Interpretation of American History''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=House |first1=Ben |title=Punic Wars & Culture Wars: Christian Essays on History and Teaching |date=2008 |page=155}}</ref> In it he argued that only \"in the light of the Christian revelation can American history be brought into proper perspective.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Singer |first1=C. Gregg |title=A Theological Interpretation of American History |date=1964 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singer, C. Gregg}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:American historians of religion]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Haverford College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Wheaton College (Illinois) faculty]]\n[[Category:Salem College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:Catawba College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Gregg Singer''' (1910 \u2013 22 March 1999) was an American historian and theologian. He was born in Philadelphia, and studied at [[Haverford College]], and the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. Singer taught at [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]], [[Salem College]], the [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[Belhaven College]], [[Catawba College]], [[Furman University]], and [[Greenville Presbyterian Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Papers\">{{cite web |title=C. Gregg Singer Papers |url=http://www.pcahistory.org/findingaids/singer.html |publisher=[[Presbyterian Church in America]] Historical Center |accessdate=12 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812053648/http://www.pcahistory.org/findingaids/singer.html |archive-date=12 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nSinger was involved in the formation of the [[Presbyterian Church in America]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Posner |first1=Sarah |title=Neo-Confederates and the Revival of \u201cTheological War\u201d for the \u201cChristian Nation\u201d |url=http://religiondispatches.org/neo-confederates-and-the-revival-of-theological-war-for-the-christian-nation/ |accessdate=12 August 2018 |work=[[Religion Dispatches]] |date=13 July 2011}}</ref> as the last President of Concerned Presbyterians, a laymans' group within the [[Presbyterian Church in the United States]].<ref name=\"Papers\" /> Singer left the PCUS in 1975, and joined the [[Associate Reformed Presbyterian Church]], before finally joining the PCA in 1987.<ref name=\"Papers\" />\n\nSinger is best known for his 1964 work, ''A Theological Interpretation of American History''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=House |first1=Ben |title=Punic Wars & Culture Wars: Christian Essays on History and Teaching |date=2008 |page=155}}</ref> In it he argued that only \"in the light of the Christian revelation can American history be brought into proper perspective.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Singer |first1=C. Gregg |title=A Theological Interpretation of American History |date=1964 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singer, C. Gregg}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:American historians of religion]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Haverford College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Wheaton College (Illinois) faculty]]\n[[Category:Salem College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:Catawba College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._Gregg_Singer"}
